Or you can just not use the junit task and launch one of the standard
test runners that come with JUnit.  I prefer the output of the
junit.textui.TestRunner, anyway, and this way you can control which
tests run in which JVMs, etc.  Here is our task:

  &lt;target name=&quot;junit.textui.alltests&quot;&gt;
        &lt;echo&gt;
========================================================================
==
 RUNNING UNIT TESTS (with suffix ${suffix})
========================================================================
==
        &lt;/echo&gt;

        &lt;java classname=&quot;junit.textui.TestRunner&quot; failonerror=&quot;yes&quot;
fork=&quot;yes&quot;&gt;
            &lt;classpath refid=&quot;test.classpath&quot;/&gt;
            &lt;arg value=&quot;com.digitalfocus.unittest.MasterTestSuite&quot;/&gt;
            &lt;sysproperty key=&quot;test.root.dir&quot; path=&quot;${classes.dir}&quot;/&gt;
            &lt;sysproperty key=&quot;test.class.suffix&quot; value=&quot;${suffix}&quot;/&gt;
        &lt;/java&gt;

        &lt;echo&gt;
========================================================================
==
 UNIT TESTS DONE
========================================================================
==
        &lt;/echo&gt;
    &lt;/target&gt;







